    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-10-21T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-10-21T01:00:00-05:00" n="683"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d683">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/14129: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hong Kong</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Southard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hong Kong</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-10-21T14:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 21, 1938—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 21—7 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Majority of information from our various and most reliable contacts in Hong Kong,
                    excepting Chinese, indicates continued progress of Japanese in direction of
                    Canton, including a movement flanking Chinese defences in order to reach that
                    city also from the north. Lungmun, north of Tsengcheng, variously reported to be
                    in Japanese hands. Japanese advance now appears to be within 25 miles of Canton.
                    Reliably reported here that American hospital and church at Waichow unmolested
                    and safe. I have been in touch with Shekki and have no information of congestion
                    of American refugees there as indicated by Linnell but am at once sending
                    representative of this office to that place to survey situation first hand.
                    Japanese Consul General here has special soldiers to insure safety Americans in
                    war zones and acts promptly on all my requests and recommendations. British
                    Ambassador to China is in Hong Kong en route to Hankow via Indo-China.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Canton, Chungking, Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Southard</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
